    Social Agreement + Moral/Ethical Boundaries: This is an excellent distillation. What we call "Laws of Man" (or "law" in general, beyond natural laws) are indeed social constructs. They are a complex, often messy, emergent outcome of:\par
\par
        Shared Values: What a majority (or powerful minority) agrees is good, bad, right, or wrong.\par
\par
        Historical Precedent: Traditions, past decisions, and cultural norms.\par
\par
        Power Dynamics: The will of those in power to enforce certain rules.\par
\par
        Practical Necessity: Rules needed for a functioning society (e.g., traffic laws).\par
\par
        Iterative Process: Laws evolve, are debated, and change over time. They are not fixed like the speed of light.\par
